05148nam a22006255i 9780300236378DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20221997ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803002363787 a10.12987/97803002363782doi  a(DE-B1597)625825  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aML410.S3bS29975 1997eb 7aMUS0000002bisacsh04a780/.922231 aErickson, Raymond, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSchubert's Vienna /cRaymond Erickson. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2022] 4c©1997  a1 online resource :b140 b/w + 20 color illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tSOURCES OF ILLUSTRATIONS -- tPART ONE Politics and Social Life -- t1 Vienna in Its European Context -- t2 People, Class Structure, and Society -- t3 The Congress of Vienna -- tPART TWO Musical Life -- t4 "Classic" and "Romantic," Beethoven and Schubert -- t5 Vienna, City of Music -- t6 Social Dancing in Schubert's World -- tPART THREE The other Arts -- t7 Architecture and Sculpture -- t8 Viennese Biedermeier Painting -- t9 The Poetry of Schubert's Songs -- t10 The Viennese Theater -- tAfterword Vienna's Schubert -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Vienna in which Franz Schubert lived for the thirty-one years of his life was a city of music, dance, and coffeehouses—a center of important achievements in the arts. But it was also the capital of an empire that was constantly at war in the composer’s youth and that became a police state during his maturity. Now, in the bicentennial of Schubert's birth, this elegantly written and richly illustrated book paints a vivid picture of the culture, society, and politics of Schubert's Vienna.Eminent authorities examine Vienna’s history and politics, class structure, and social conventions. They describe private and public entertainments, including music and dance, as well as classical and popular Viennese theater, both of which achieved special greatness in the early nineteenth century. They investigate the historical layers of architecture and sculpture that preserved Vienna’s past or reflected the imperatives of Schubert’s time. They analyze genres of painting that exemplified or went beyond the ideals of Biedermeier society. And they discuss literary currents reflected in (or absent from) the poetry that fired Schubert’s musical imagination.This charming book, which enriches our view of Schubert and the city in which he lived, will be treasured by both lovers of music and lovers of Vienna.Contributors: Elizabeth Aldrich, Jane K. Brown, Raymond Erickson, Gerbert Frodl, Alice M. Hanson, Waltraud Heindl, Ernst Hilmar, Thomas DaCosta Kaufmann, Enno Kraehe, Leon Plantinga, Simon Williams  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aArts, AustrianzAustriazVienna. 0aMusiczAustriazViennay19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh1 aAldrich, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Jane K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErickson, Raymond, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrodl, Gerbert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHanson, Alice M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeindl, Waltraud, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHilmar, Ernst, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaufmann, Thomas Dacosta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKraehe, Enno, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular